<worksheet xml:id="week12-handout">
  <title>Week 11-12 Handout-Boundary Value Problems in Other Coordinate Systems</title>

    <introduction>
        <statement> <p>
         To solve a PDE on the domain whose shape is a 2D disk, it is much more 
        convenient to represent the solution in terms of the polar coordinate system 
        than in terms of the usual Cartesian coordinate system.

        For example, the behavior of the drum surface when hitting it by a stick would 
        be best described by the solution of the wave equation in the polar coordinate system.

        We will discuss the following topics related to <term> BVP in other coordinate systems (Chap 14)</term>:
      <ul>
        <li> <p>Week 11: Polar Coordinates (14.1)  </p>   </li>
        <li> <p>Week 12: Cylindrical Coordinates (14.2)</p> </li>
      </ul>  </p>
        </statement>
    </introduction>
    <remark xml:id="rem-polar-rectangle">
      <title>Relationship between Polar Coordinates and Rectangle Coordinates</title>
      <statement> <p>
        <md>
          <mrow xml:id="eq-x-y" number="yes"> 
             x=r\cos\theta \amp \amp  y=r\sin\theta </mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="eq-r-theta" number="yes"> 
            r^2=x^2+y^2 \amp  \amp \tan\theta=\frac{y}{x} </mrow>
        </md>       

        <figure xml:id="fig-polar">
          <caption>Relationship between polar coordinates and rectangle coordinates. </caption>
            <image width="80%" alignment="center">
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.8]

                  % Axes
                  \draw[->] (-0.2,0) -- (4.2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                  \draw[->] (0,-0.2) -- (0,3.2) node[above] {$y$};

                  % Point values
                  \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                  \coordinate (P) at (3,2);
                  \coordinate (X) at (3,0);
                  \coordinate (Y) at (0,2);

                  % Radius r
                  \draw[thick] (O) -- (P) node[midway,above left] {$r$};

                  % Right triangle
                  \draw[dashed] (P) -- (X);
                  \draw[dashed] (P) -- (Y);

                  % Horizontal and vertical sides
                  \draw[decorate, decoration={brace,mirror,raise=3pt}]
                        (O) -- (X) node[midway, yshift=-10pt] {$x = r\cos\theta$};
                  \draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=5pt}]
                        (O) -- (Y) node[midway, xshift=-11pt, rotate=90] {$y = r\sin\theta$};

                  % Angle theta
                  \draw (0.8,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=34,radius=0.8];
                  \node at (1.0,0.3) {$\theta$};

                  % Point label
                  \fill (P) circle (2pt);
                  \node[above right] at (P) {$(x,y)$};

                  \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
             </image>
        </figure> 

      </p>

      </statement>
      
      
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def-Laplacian-Polar">
      <title>Laplace's Equation in Polar Coordinates</title>
        <statement>
        <p>  The <term>Laplace's equation </term> in <m>R^2</m> in terms of the 
          <term>Cartesian</term> <m>(x,y)</m> coordinate system is:
          <md xml:id="eq-laplace-rec" number="yes">
            \nabla^2 u=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}=u_{xx}+u_{yy}=0.
          </md>
          From <xref ref="rem-polar-rectangle"/>, we can compute partial derivatives of 
          <m>r, \theta</m> with respect to <m>x, y</m> from <xref ref="eq-r-theta"/> using 
          <term>implicit differentiation</term>:
          <md>
            <mrow> 2r\frac{\partial r}{\partial x}=2x, \amp \amp 2r\frac{\partial r}{\partial y}=2y </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-1st-r-xy" number="yes"> \Rightarrow \frac{\partial r}{\partial x}=\frac{x}{r}=\cos\theta, \amp \amp \frac{\partial r}{\partial y}=\frac{y}{r}=\sin\theta </mrow>
          </md>
          <md>
            <mrow> \sec^2\theta\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}=-\frac{y}{x^2},\amp \amp \sec^2\theta\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial y}=\frac{1}{x} </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-1st-theta-xy" number="yes">\Rightarrow  \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}=-\frac{y\cos^2\theta}{x^2}=-\frac{\sin\theta}{r}, 
              \amp \amp \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial y}=\frac{\cos^2\theta}{x}=\frac{\cos\theta}{r} </mrow>
          </md>
          
          Next, we start rewriting <m>\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}</m> and <m>\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}</m>
          using <term>Chain Rule</term>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} = \amp \frac{\partial u}{\partial r}\frac{\partial r}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x} </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-1st-u-r" number="yes">
              = \amp \cos\theta\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}-\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}</mrow>
          </md>
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}= \amp \frac{\partial u}{\partial r}\frac{\partial r}{\partial y}+\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial y} </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-1st-u-theta" number="yes"> 
                   =\amp \sin\theta\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{\cos\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta} </mrow>
          </md>        
          Then we further compute <m>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}</m> and <m>\frac{\partial ^2 u}{\partial y^2}</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2} = \amp \frac{\partial }{\partial x}\left\{\cos\theta\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}-\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\right\}</mrow>
            <mrow> \frac{\partial }{\partial x}\left\{\cos\theta\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}\right\}=\amp \frac{\partial \cos\theta}{\partial x}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\cos\theta\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left\{\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}\right\} </mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp-\sin\theta\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r} +\cos\theta\left\{\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta\partial r}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial r^2}\frac{\partial r}{\partial x}\right\} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{\sin^2\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r} +\cos\theta\left\{-\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial \theta\partial r}+\cos\theta\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial r^2}\right\} </mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{\partial}{\partial x } \left\{\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\right\}
              =\amp \frac{\partial \frac{\sin\theta}{r}}{\partial x}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}+\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\frac{\partial }{\partial x}\left\{\frac{\partial u}{\partial\theta}\right\}</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp \frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\left\{\frac{\partial \frac{\sin\theta}{r}}{\partial \theta}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial \frac{\sin\theta}{r}}{\partial r}\frac{\partial r}{\partial x}\right\} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp +\frac{\sin\theta}{r}\left\{\frac{\partial ^2 u}{\partial \theta^2}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial \theta\partial r}\frac{\partial r}{\partial x}\right\} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\left\{\frac{-2\cos\theta\sin\theta}{r^2}\right\}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta^2}\left\{-\frac{\sin^2\theta}{r^2}\right\}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta\partial r}\left\{\frac{\sin\theta\cos\theta}{r}\right\} </mrow>
          </md>
          Thus, 
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\amp \frac{\sin^2\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r} -\frac{2\sin\theta\cos\theta}{r}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial \theta\partial r}+\cos^2\theta\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial r^2}</mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-u-xx" number="yes">\amp +\frac{2\cos\theta\sin\theta}{r^2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}+\frac{\sin^2\theta}{r^2}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta^2}</mrow>
          </md>
          
        Similarly, we can derive 
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2} =\amp \frac{\cos^2\theta}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r} +\frac{2\sin\theta\cos\theta}{r}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial \theta\partial r}+\sin^2\theta\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial r^2}</mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-u-yy" number="yes">\amp -\frac{2\cos\theta\sin\theta}{r^2}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}+\frac{\cos^2\theta}{r^2}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta^2}</mrow>
        </md>
        Adding <xref ref="eq-u-xx"/> and <xref ref="eq-u-yy"/>, we obtain
        <md>
          \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial r^2}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^2}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta^2}.
        </md>
        Thus, the <term>Laplace's equation in polar coordinates</term> is
        <md xml:id="eq-laplace-polar" number="yes">
          \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial r^2}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^2}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial\theta^2}=0
        </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the Laplace's Equation <xref ref="eq-laplace-polar"/> for steady state temperature in a circular plate with the radius 
          of <m>r</m> and the bounary condition of <m>u(c, \theta)=f(\theta), 0\lt \theta\lt 2\pi.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Consider the steady-state temperature <m>u(r,\theta)</m> in the semicircular plate below:
          <figure xml:id="fig-semi-circle">
          <caption>Boundary conditions of Steady-State temperature $u(r,\theta)$ on a semicircular plate  </caption>
            <image width="80%" alignment="center">
              <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.8]
                  \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta,decorations.pathreplacing}

                  % Parameters
                  \def\R{4}
                  \def\ang{40}

                  % Axes
                  \draw[->] (-4.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                  \draw[->] (0,0) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {$y$};

                  % Shaded semicircle
                  \fill[brown!40]
                    (-\R,0) arc[start angle=180,end angle=0,radius=\R] -- cycle;

                  % Semicircle boundary
                  \draw[thick,blue]
                    (-\R,0) arc[start angle=180,end angle=0,radius=\R];

                  % Diameter
                  \draw[thick] (-\R,0) -- (\R,0);

                  % Polar angle theta at origin
                  \draw[thick] (1.2,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=180,radius=1.2];
                  \node at (-0.1,1.4) {$\theta=\pi$};

                  % Dashed radius line
                  \draw[dashed,->] (0,0) -- ({\R*cos(\ang)},{\R*sin(\ang)})
                    node[midway,right] {$c$};

                  % Boundary labels
                  \node[above right] at (2.6,3.3) {$u=u_0$};

                  \node[below] at (2.5,-0.4) {$u=0\ \text{at}\ \theta=0$};
                  \node[below] at (-2.8,-0.4) {$u=0\ \text{at}\ \theta=\pi$};

                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>  
              </image>
              </figure>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>   <p> Write out the entire model.     </p>     </li>
          <li>  <p> Find the solution <m>u(r,\theta)</m> that satifies the given boundary conditions. </p>  </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-heatwave-Polar">
      <title>Cylindrical Coordinates</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li> <p><term>Heat Equation in polar coordinate system</term>:
            <md>
              u_t=k\left(u_{rr}+\frac{1}{r}u_r+\frac{1}{r^2}u_{\theta\theta}\right), k>0:\mbox{diffusivity}
            </md>             </p>     </li>
            <li><p><term>Wave Equation in polar coordinate system</term>:
            <md>
              u_{tt}=c^2\left(u_{rr}+\frac{1}{r}u_r+\frac{1}{r^2}u_{\theta\theta}\right), c>0:\mbox{wave velocity}
            </md>      
              The above two equations are in <term>cylindrical coordinates</term> since
              the <term> time <m>t</m> </term> gives the 3rd axis from the circular plate which produces
              a cylinder with infinite length as <m>t\gt 0.</m> </p> </li>
              
            <li> <p><term>Laplacian in Cylindrical Coordinates</term>: 
              Consider a domain of a cylinder for the Laplace's Equation: <m>x=r\cos\theta,y=r\sin\theta, z=z</m>
              <md>
                \nabla^2 u=\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial r^2}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^2}\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial \theta^2}+\frac{\partial^2u}{\partial z^2}
              </md>
              
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>

        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
</worksheet>

